# Cursor Rules: Chapter Outline Writing

<introduction>
Guidelines for creating structured, actionable chapter outlines following the established DataCamp course format. Emphasizes brevity, timing precision, and clear learning progression.
</introduction>

## Core Structure Requirements

<chapter_header>
```markdown
# Chapter X: [Action Verb] - [Focus Area]

**Theme:** [Emotional transformation - from X to Y]
**Message:** [Core pedagogical principle or approach]

## Chapter Arc
- **X.1:** [Learning type] (concept/build/methodology)
- **X.2:** [Learning type] (concept/build/methodology)  
- **X.3:** [Learning type] (concept/build/methodology)
```
</chapter_header>

<lesson_structure>
```markdown
## Lesson X.Y: "[Actionable Title]"

**Target:** XXX-XXX words, ~X.X-X.X minutes  
**Objectives:** [2-3 specific, measurable learning outcomes]

### Script Structure

**[Section Name] (XXs)**
- [Key point with specific detail]
- [Action or example]

### Slides
1. [Slide description with specific visual/content]
2. [Slide description with specific visual/content]
```
</lesson_structure>

## Writing Guidelines

<brevity_principles>
<timing_precision>Always include specific word counts (250-300) and time estimates (~2.5-3 minutes)</timing_precision>
<bullet_efficiency>Use concise bullets, not paragraphs. Each bullet = one key point or action</bullet_efficiency>
<specific_examples>Include concrete examples, not abstract concepts ("meditation timer" not "simple app")</specific_examples>
<time_allocation>Break script sections into timed segments that add up to total target time</time_allocation>
</brevity_principles>

<content_structure>
<transformational_theme>Frame each chapter as an emotional/skill transformation journey</transformational_theme>
<progressive_complexity>Structure lessons as: Concept → Hands-on → Framework/Methodology</progressive_complexity>
<bridge_language>Include explicit transitions between lessons ("Next: You'll build...", "Bridge from 1.1:")</bridge_language>
<actionable_titles>Use active, specific lesson titles that preview the outcome</actionable_titles>
</content_structure>

<script_formatting>
<opening_hooks>Start each lesson with a compelling hook or bridge from previous content</opening_hooks>
<timed_segments>Break scripts into 15-180 second segments with clear focus</timed_segments>
<practical_examples>Include specific examples with concrete comparisons (traditional vs. new approach)</practical_examples>
<clear_transitions>End each lesson with explicit setup for the next lesson</clear_transitions>
</script_formatting>

## Template Patterns

<lesson_types>
<concept_lesson>
**Target:** 250-300 words, ~2.5-3 minutes
**Structure:** Hook → Analogy → Definition → Example → Bridge
**Focus:** Mindset shift, paradigm explanation
</concept_lesson>

<build_lesson>
**Target:** 400-450 words, ~4.5-5 minutes
**Structure:** Setup → Tool Tour → Build Process → Insights → Wrap
**Focus:** Hands-on experience, proving concepts work
</build_lesson>

<framework_lesson>
**Target:** 350-400 words, ~3.5-4 minutes
**Structure:** Bridge → Framework Breakdown → Application → Summary
**Focus:** Systematic methodology, replicable process
</framework_lesson>
</lesson_types>

<slide_specifications>
<visual_focus>Each slide should have one clear visual concept or comparison</visual_focus>
<progression_logic>Slides should follow the script structure exactly</progression_logic>
<specific_content>Describe specific slide content, not generic placeholders</specific_content>
<transition_slides>Include explicit transition/preview slides for lesson bridges</transition_slides>
</slide_specifications>

## Voice and Tone

<authentic_voice>
<direct_language>Use active voice, specific verbs, avoid generic marketing speak</direct_language>
<problem_focused>Lead with problems learners face, not features or tools</problem_focused>
<conversational_bridges>Write transitions as natural conversation flow</conversational_bridges>
<outcome_emphasis>Focus on what learners will accomplish, not what they'll learn</outcome_emphasis>
</authentic_voice>

<avoid_patterns>
<generic_language>Avoid vague terms like "explore," "discover," "journey" without specifics</generic_language>
<feature_focus>Don't lead with tool capabilities; lead with learner problems</feature_focus>
<academic_tone>Avoid formal academic language; use conversational, practical tone</academic_tone>
<unnecessary_complexity>Don't overcomplicate simple concepts with jargon</unnecessary_complexity>
</avoid_patterns>

## Exercise Integration

<exercise_structure>
```markdown
## Exercises

**X.1:** [Video type] + [Interactive type] + [Assessment type]
**X.2:** [Video type] + [Interactive type] + [Assessment type]
**X.3:** [Video type] + [Interactive type] + [Assessment type]
```
</exercise_structure>

<exercise_types>
<video_options>Video, Interactive video, Guided walkthrough</video_options>
<interactive_options>Build follow-along, Interactive coding, Tool simulation</interactive_options>
<assessment_options>MCQ, Classification, Matching, Sequencing, Fill-in-the-blank</assessment_options>
</exercise_types>

## Quality Checklist

<content_quality>
- [ ] Chapter theme shows clear emotional/skill transformation
- [ ] Each lesson has specific word count and time target
- [ ] Script segments are timed and add up to lesson total
- [ ] Concrete examples replace abstract concepts
- [ ] Slides match script structure exactly
- [ ] Exercises combine multiple learning modalities
- [ ] Voice is conversational and problem-focused
- [ ] Transitions between lessons are explicit and smooth
</content_quality>

<structural_quality>
- [ ] Three-lesson arc follows concept → build → framework pattern
- [ ] Each lesson has clear, actionable title
- [ ] Objectives are specific and measurable
- [ ] Script structure uses consistent timing format
- [ ] Slide descriptions are specific, not generic
- [ ] Exercise types are varied and appropriate
</structural_quality> 